[[File:Mrs Winslows Soothing Syrup bottle.JPG|thumb|Moulded on this 5-inch tall glass bottle are the inscriptions MRS. WINSLOWS / SOOTHING SYRUP / CURTIS & PERKINS / PROPRIETORS]]

'''Mrs. Winslow's Soothing Syrup''' is a [[patent medicine]] supposedly compounded by Mrs. Charlotte N. Winslow, and first marketed by her son-in-law Jeremiah Curtis and Benjamin A. Perkins of Bangor, Maine, USA{{r|WoodLibrary}} in 1849.{{r|MuseumOfDrugs}}  The formula consisted of [[Morphine|morphine sulphate]] (65 mg per [[fluid ounce]]), [[sodium carbonate]], spirits foeniculi, and [[aqua ammonia]]. It was claimed that it was "likely to sooth any human or animal", and it effectively quieted restless infants and small children especially for [[teething]].{{r|LCDL}} It was widely marketed in the UK and the US. As well as newspapers, the company used various media to promote its product, including recipe books, calendars, and trade cards.<ref>''J Hist Dent.'' 2000 Nov;48(3):99–105</ref>

In 1911 the [[American Medical Association]] issued a publication titled "Nostrums And Quackery" in which, in a section called "Baby Killers", it incriminated Mrs. Winslow's Soothing Syrup.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/nostrumsquackery00amerrich |title=Nostrums and Quackery; Articles on the Nostrum Evil and Quackery |year=1911 |location=Chicago, IL. |website=Internet Archive |publisher=American Medical Association |page=318}}</ref> The product was nevertheless not withdrawn from sale until 1930.{{r|WoodLibrary}}

In 1879 the English composer [[Edward Elgar]] wrote an early musical work, part of his ''Harmony Music'' for a wind quintet, which he titled ''Mrs. Winslow's soothing syrup''. In Woody Guthrie's 1940 Dustbowl Ballad, "Tom Joad", Grandpa Joad is given soothing syrup before he dies.{{r|Guthrie}}

