{{italic title}} '''''Stone's Justices' Manual''''' is a book published by [[LexisNexis Butterworths]]. It is "the standard work on summary procedure".<ref>Card, Richard (editor). [[Card, Cross and Jones: Criminal Law]]. Twelfth Edition. Butterworths. 1992. {{ISBN|0-406-00086-7}}. ¶3.13.</ref> It displaced Burn's ''Justices of the Peace'' as the standard work on that subject from 1850 onwards.<ref>David Bentley. ''English Criminal Justice in the Nineteenth Century''. The Hambledon Press. [[Continuum International Publishing Group]]. 1998. {{ISBN|9781852851354}}. Page 23, note 17. [https://books.google.com/books?id=u4OtrN-Ha4EC&pg=PA23#v=onepage&q&f=false Digitized copy] from Google Books.</ref> By 1914, it was old, well-established and formidably large.<ref>Alexander, G Glover. ''The Administration of Justice in Criminal Matters: (In England and Wales)''. Cambridge University Press. 1915. Reissued 1919. Reprinted 2010. {{ISBN|978-0-521-18348-2}}. Pages [https://books.google.com/books?id=0IF_aYG4dBIC&pg=PR5#v=onepage&q&f=false v] and [https://books.google.com/books?id=0IF_aYG4dBIC&pg=PA215#v=onepage&q&f=false 215]. Digitized copy from Google Books.</ref>
''Stone's Justices' Manual'' is published in June of every year, with an updating supplement published in October. An accompanying CD-ROM contains the full text plus additional resources such as the [[All England Law Reports]].
''Stone's Justices' Manual'' covers civil procedure, criminal law and litigation and provides comprehensive coverage of all new and amended legislation affecting the magistrates' courts. It also includes hundreds of new cases that set precedents or clarify particular principles of law.
