'''Tariff engineering''' is a [[loophole]] whereby an importer pays a lower [[tariff]] by "adapting the item [being imported] so that [the importer doesn't] have to pay any levy".<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-45875405</ref> The began following the 1881 US Supreme Court case of ''[[Merrit v. Walsh]]'', which dealt with the classification of imported sugar.<ref>https://www.joc.com/tariff-engineering-it-still-viable_20010924.html</ref><ref>http://www.barnesrichardson.com/4E8FDC/assets/files/News/tariff-engineering.pdf</ref> An example of tariff engineering is the [[Chicken tax]], related to the importation of trucks into the United States.<ref>http://www.autonews.com/article/20161203/OEM/312059954/m-b-finds-a-better-way-around-the-chicken-tax</ref>
